forms

This is an example of how you can set the placeholder text within a very simple form to size proprotionately to it. 

You can change the font size value to suit. Ie 4vh or 2 vh et.
Line height nicely separates the boxes vertically (but it also equally separates the boxe's titles). 


SIMPLE FORM
HTML
<form class="header-search__form" action="submit.php" method="post">
          <textarea id="message" name="message" rows="1" cols="50"  placeholder="Search"></textarea>
          <button type="submit">&lt; &lt; GO &gt; &gt;</button>
    </form> 
#############

CSS 
input {height:43px; width:280px; }

input::placeholder {font-size:3vh;}
input {font-size:3vh;}

Button
button {background:rgba(27,108,166,0.5);}



********************
Styling a <select> box
select.widget-box-appointment {
appearance:none; <!--Gets rid of default styling so you can style it your way-->
width: 90%; <!--Sizes the box 90% of it's containing div -->
font-size:1rem; <!--Sets the size of the inner text -->
border:1px solid #777; 
border-radius:1%; 
padding:15px;}

<form> <select class="widget-box-appointment"> <option> Get connected </option> <option> option 2 </option> </select> </form>
********************




BELOW IS A LOGIN FORM 
<form action="#" method="post">
    <div>
      <label for="username">Username:</label>
      <input type="text" id="username" name="username" required>
    </div>
    <div>
      <label for="password">Password:</label>
      <input type="password" id="password" name="password" required>
    </div>
    <div>
      <input type="checkbox" id="remember" name="remember">
      <label for="remember">Remember Me</label>
    </div>
    <div>
      <button type="submit">Login</button>
    </div>
  </form>
  
